if the page is slower to hydrate, neither link is visible immediately, so `setStoreVisible` is `false`, and then `checkAvailabilityLink.waitFor` also fails.\n- Fix: use a proper `race` between the two locators, or use `waitFor` with proper timeout on `setYourStoreLink`, then catch and try the alternative.\n\nFor TC-83240 (Login):\n- Current code has `timeout: 30_000`. The error context shows 15s which is old.\n- But the login might still fail if the UAT site has changed how `/myaccount` redirects work.\n- The current `navigate()` in BasePage calls `waitForAppShell()` which waits for `header`. The login page may not have a header, triggering the catch block which clicks body. This might interfere with login page rendering.\n- Better approach: after navigating to `/myaccount`, wait for `networkidle` or wait for the URL to contain `/login`, then wait for the form.\n\nLet me think about concrete fixes:\n\n**Fix 1: TC-83232 — Newsletter**\nThe issue is that `div.bg-primary input[type=\"email\"]` is timing out. \n- Try using `scrollIntoViewIfNeeded()` directly on the locator to trigger lazy rendering\n- Use a more gradual scroll with `page.evaluate`\n- Add a retry with `page.reload()` if the element doesn't appear (unlikely to help)\n- The most likely fix: scroll to bottom repeatedly AND also try `page.evaluate` to force intersection observer trigger, then use `waitFor` with longer timeout\n\nActually the real issue might be that the newsletter section is rendered by Builder.io in an iframe. Let me check if we need to look inside iframes.\n\nFor the home-page spec, the scroll loop already does 5 × scroll-to-bottom + 600ms wait. If after 3s total the element is still not visible, it might genuinely be in an iframe.\n\n**Fix for TC-83232:** \n1. After the scroll loop, try `scrollIntoViewIfNeeded()` on the locator itself\n2. If that doesn't work, the element might be in an iframe - but we can't easily verify that without running the test\n3. Alternative: increase the scroll attempts and delay, or use `page.locator` with frame access\n\n**Fix 2: TC-83238 — In-Store Pickup**\nThe `isVisible()` issue: In Playwright, `locator.isVisible()` does NOT accept a timeout. It returns immediately. So:\n```typescript\nconst setStoreVisible = await this.setYourStoreLink\n    .isVisible({ timeout: 3_000 }) // timeout is IGNORED\n    .catch(() => false);\n```\nThis always returns false or true immediately. Need to use `waitFor` with a try/catch instead.\n\nFix:\n```typescript\nasync openStoreSelectorDialog(): Promise<void> {\n    // Scroll the fulfillment area into view\n    await this.inStorePickupRadio\n        .scrollIntoViewIfNeeded({ timeout: 10_000 })\n        .catch(() => undefined);\n\n    // Wait briefly for elements to mount after scroll\n    await this.page.waitForTimeout(1_000);\n\n    const checkAvailabilityLink = this.page\n        .locator('p.cursor-pointer')\n        .filter({ hasText: /check availability at other stores/i })\n        .first();\n\n    // Try \"Set your store\" first (no store set). Use waitFor with short timeout.\n    // If it doesn't appear, fall back to \"Check Availability at other stores\".\n    let setStoreVisible = false;\n    try {\n        await this.setYourStoreLink.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 5_000 });\n        setStoreVisible = true;\n    } catch {\n        setStoreVisible = false;\n    }\n\n    if (setStoreVisible) {\n        await this.setYourStoreLink.click();\n    } else {\n        await checkAvailabilityLink.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 12_000 });\n        await checkAvailabilityLink.click();\n    }\n\n    await this.storeSelectorDialog.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 10_000 });\n}\n```\n\n**Fix 3: TC-83240 — Login**\nThe error shows `timeout: 15_000` at line 28. Current code has `timeout: 30_000` at line 34. So the tests are running with OLD compiled code? Or the current file doesn't match what I think.\n\nWait — looking again at the current LoginPage.ts:\n- Line 30: `async login(email: string, password: string): Promise<void> {`\n- Line 31: `await this.navigate('/myaccount');`\n- Line 34: `await this.emailInput.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 30_000 });`\n\nThe error context shows:\n```\nat ../pages/LoginPage.ts:28\n26 |     async login(email: string, password: string): Promise<void> {\n27 |         await this.navigate('/myaccount');\n> 28 |         await this.emailInput.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 15_000 });\n```\n\nThis shows the OLD code (15_000). So the test was run with the OLD file. The current file has already been updated to 30_000. But the failure persists (user says these are current failures), so either:\n1. The 30_000 is still not enough, OR\n2. There's another issue with login page navigation\n\nThe `navigate('/myaccount')` calls `waitForAppShell()` which waits for `header`. On the login page, there may not be a header, so after 20s it clicks body and continues. But this body click on the login page might interact with something and cause issues.\n\nBetter fix for login:\n- Don't use the base `navigate()` for login — instead use raw `page.goto()` and handle login page specifics\n- OR: wait for URL to be on login page before waiting for form\n\nActually the issue is more likely: the `waitForAppShell()` tries to find `header`, fails (login page might not have one or has a different one), clicks body which might dismiss a cookie banner but also might click on something on the form. Then `emailInput.waitFor` times out because the body click disrupted something.\n\nFix: In `login()`, after `navigate()`, wait for the URL to contain `/login` or `/myaccount/login` before waiting for the email input. Also add a `page.waitForURL(/login/)` call.\n\nActually wait — the `navigate()` base class already calls `waitForAppShell()`. If the login page has a `header` element, this will work. On UAT, the login page probably does have a header (same site shell).\n\nThe real fix might be:\n1. After `navigate('/myaccount')`, wait for URL to settle on the login page (since it redirects)\n2. Then wait for form with a longer timeout\n\nLet me write the fixes now.\n"}}
